summaries.title: Balancing Pressure, Pride, and Belonging
summaries.summaryText: Daniel expressed pride in representing his family’s aspirations but also noted ongoing struggles with imposter syndrome. He values belonging through peer groups that normalize his experiences as a first-gen student of color in STEM. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Leadership and Mentorship in Engineering Design Projects
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah described how leading senior design teams strengthened her confidence in project management and technical problem-solving. She reflected on mentorship as a core component of her academic identity, often supporting younger women of color navigating engineering culture. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Building Community Through Cultural Organizations
summaries.summaryText: Participation in SHPE and campus cultural centers provided Maria a sense of belonging and identity affirmation. These communities offered emotional support and mentorship that she could not easily find in her department. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Recognizing Privilege and Peer Disparities in Engineering Education
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: First-Generation Challenges in Navigating University Systems
summaries.summaryText: Maria described difficulty understanding financial aid processes and navigating academic advising resources. She relied heavily on peer networks and informal guidance, noting that the institutional language often assumed prior family familiarity with college systems. [Part 3/4]

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 4]

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 1]

quotes.quoteText: When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasn’t just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 3]

quotes.quoteText: When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Encourage faculty to include ‘learning journeys’ in course introductions
Develop short workshops on inclusive teaching practices

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals
